No greenwashing bulls**t here 

Here is part 4 sharing my favourite small, sustainable, slow fashion brands. Thereâ€™s a lot of greenwashing going on with high street and fast fashion brands so I wanted to continue to shine a light on small brands who do things a bit differently.

@picklesknitwear I found this brand through my Vinted suggestions and their algorithm is spot on. The slogan in itself is incredible and amazingly all their knits are machine knitted by one person in London using locally sourced wool. Everything is really fun and quirky yet simple making them easy to style and wear. 

@bontelondon create colourful joyful clothes with the most beautiful fabrics and prints using ethically sourced materials from India. This gingham vest is my favourite from their most recent collection. I love all the attention to detail and little features to their pieces which is what makes this brand so special and unique. 

@the_nion_edit Nicola designs bold and colourful womenswear in London from end of roll materials, everything is made to order to reduce waste. This shiny silver cotton skirt is so versatile for all seasons and there are also amazing dresses, shirts and lots of leopard print. 

@threadthespool Iâ€™ve been asked about this top so many times over the festive period! Itâ€™s so good I wore the dress version on Christmas Day. All made to order in Yorkshire, think comfortable, ruffly, feminine and thereâ€™s bridal and childrenâ€™s wear too. I have such a long list of pieces I want to try. 

@elwinstudio this skirt has become my staple go-to style, I now have it in 3 colours/fabrics because it is just perfection. Made in East London from deadstock materials and natural fabrics they have perfected the basics and essentials you need for your wardrobe. Next on my wishlist is one of their British wool knits. 

@caroline.dickinson_ Caroline sources vintage menâ€™s shirts and adds a creative twist to them by hand printing with a unique design in her Waterloo studio. There are classic denim, ginghams and stripes, each shirt is one of a kind and her drops sell out fast, Iâ€™ve got my eye on a denim one next. 

